INT. FRONTIER MISSION CONTROL - DAY

Every console manned, every screen the same: the gray surface coming up under the lander's camera, dust beginning to streak.

BRANDT (V.O.):
(on the loop)
Two hundred feet. Down at three. Picking up some dust.

INT. ROY'S DINER - CONTINUOUS

Standing room only. The TV huge in the corner. Nobody eats.

INT. JOSS'S TRUCK, RIDGE ROAD - CONTINUOUS

Joss and Danny shoulder to shoulder in the cab, a phone propped on the dash streaming the feed, the ham rig silent beside it.

BRANDT (V.O.):
(on the phone, compressed)
Fifty feet. Forty. Contact light — engine stop.

The dust settles on every screen in America. HARMONY ONE stands on the Sea of Tranquility, primer-white, flagless.

The diner watches, still. Somebody's coffee goes cold untouched.

INT. CARGO BAY - CONTINUOUS

No one on Earth sees this. Touchdown slammed the crate rack. Straps took the load wrong, something in Crate C slid half a foot and stopped hard.

Cricket keys the mic, his own breath still catching.

CRICKET:
(low)
Sound off.

DUTCH (FILTERED):
Here.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
Here.

A beat. Nothing from Crate C.

CRICKET:
Stitch.

Nothing.

CRICKET:
(sharper now)
Elmore.

A wet, ugly cough comes over the channel.

STITCH (FILTERED):
(raspy)
...M'fine. Bit clean through my tongue is all.

A breath goes around the net.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
Don't you go quiet on this net again, Colonel.

STITCH (FILTERED):
Copy.

EXT. SEA OF TRANQUILITY - LUNAR DAY

Silence and glare. The lander's shadow long across the regolith.

The crew works the base-station deployment: BRANDT and LINDQVIST wrestling a solar array true, SHEN anchoring a comms mast, all three helmet-cams feeding Earth. A camera boom pans slow across the site for the broadcast.

Behind the lander, in its blind spot, the cargo ramp is down.

Four crates stand open on the ramp, lids back, couches empty.

Four suited figures move in the lander's shadow. Suits fifty years old, patched and re-hosed, the NASA meatball bright on every chest. On one wrist cuff, a small brass museum tag turns on its wire.

They cross-load gear from crates E and F onto the BACKUP ROVER: tarped bundles, latched cases, a long soft-sided sleeve strapped diagonal. Practiced and unhurried, not one move wasted.

The last man aboard is the tallest. He settles into the rover's rear rack seat, raps the fender twice — pause — twice.

The rover pulls away from the lander in a slow arc, out of the shadow and into the sun, four men and their freight aboard. Tire tracks unspool behind it across ground no one has touched in fifty years.

It gets small against the gray. Then it drops behind a rise and is gone.

Behind it, the tires throw a rooster-tail of dust that doesn't billow the way dust should. No air to hold it. It arcs, clean and ballistic, and comes down all at once, in one place, unnaturally neat.

At the base station, Brandt straightens from the solar array, turns to check the horizon out of pure habit, and stops.

He stares north. A thin haze, catching the sun, exactly where nothing should be moving.

ON THE ROVER — the four of them go still. Engine cut. Parked exactly where the rise should hide them, and doesn't quite. Cricket's hand stays flat on the throttle. Nobody breathes into a mic.

Brandt watches the horizon. Three seconds. Four.

LINDQVIST (O.S.):
(over comms)
Commander, panel four's ready for your sign-off.

A beat longer. Then Brandt turns back to the array, already reaching for his checklist.

BRANDT:
(on the loop)
Base station nominal. Harmony One, beginning retrieval operations at first light tomorrow, per the program.

Behind him, far off over the rise, the last of the dust settles.

CUT TO:
